{{draft}}{{Expand Japanese}}
[[File:Kotohira Kotohira-gu Goninbyakushou 1.JPG|thumb|Umbrella merchants selling the candy on the approach to the shrine]]
'''Kamiyo Ame''' is a traditional Japanese [[:en:Yuzu|yuzu]]-flavored hard candy associated with [[Kotohira-gū]],<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|title=Kamiyo Ame Candy|url=https://omotenashinippon.jp/selection/en/prize/2200-02-056/|access-date=2023-09-17|website=おもてなしセレクション（OMOTENASHI Selection）|language=en-US}}</ref>.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Kagawa {{!}} Pilgrimage to the Kotohira-gu Shrine {{!}} Authentic Japan: Setouchi|url=https://www.setouchi.travel/en/see-and-do/kotohira-gu-shrine/|access-date=2023-09-17|website=www.setouchi.travel|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|date=2023-04-05|title=Once-in-a-lifetime Konpira-san! Let's visit Kotohira Shrine|url=https://thegate12.com/article/205|access-date=2023-09-17|website=THE GATE}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Konpirasan – the famous Pilgrimage of Shikoku (Kagawa)|url=http://setouchifinder.com/en/detail/4242?pg=2|access-date=2023-09-17|website=Stouchi Finder|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Kotohira-gu|url=https://ikidane-nippon.com/en/spots/kotohira-gu|access-date=2023-09-17|website=Ikidane Nippon|language=en-US}}</ref> commonly known as Konpira-san, a Shinto shrine in Kagawa Prefecture. This confection has been offered at the shrine for over 700 years, symbolizing good fortune and divine blessings.<ref name=":1">https://omotenashinippon.jp/selection/en/prize/2200-02-056/?utm_source=chatgpt.com</ref> 

The candy is notable for its golden, amber-like appearance, reflecting the shrine's aesthetic. Traditionally, Kamiyo Ame is sold by five families known as "Gonin Byakusho" (Five Farmers), who have exclusive rights to vend the candy within the shrine's precincts. These families have maintained the confection's production methods and cultural significance through generations. <ref name=":1" />

A unique aspect of Kamiyo Ame is its consumption method: the candy is broken into pieces using a small golden hammer, allowing it to be shared among individuals. This practice embodies the communal and auspicious nature of the confection. <ref>https://guidememo.com/konpira/?utm_source=chatgpt.com</ref><ref name=":0" />

==Japanese content==

[[File:Kotohira Kotohira-gu Goninbyakushou 1.JPG|thumb|right|"Kasano-shita shōnin" (merchants under umbrellas) selling Kamiyo-ame along the approach to Kotohira-gū]]

'''Kamiyo-ame''' (加美代飴) is a type of [[amber candy (bekkō-ame)|bekkō-ame]] (amber candy) sold along the approach to [[Kotohira-gū]] in [[Kotohira, Kagawa]] Prefecture. It is shaped like a [[fan]]{{R|朱|る}}.

== Overview ==
This candy is a type of [[bekkō-ame]] (amber candy), and it is traditionally eaten by breaking it into pieces with a small hammer that comes with it{{R|朱|る}}.

The name “Kamiyo” (加美代) is derived from “kamiyo” (神代), meaning the “Age of the Gods.”{{R|和}}

Five candy shops sell Kamiyo-ame just past the large gate (ōmon) on the approach. These five shops, which are permitted to do business within the shrine grounds, are known as the “Gonin Hyakushō” (Five Merchants){{R|和|コ}}. The vendors who sell candy under umbrellas inside the main gate are called “kasa no shita shōnin” (umbrella-shade merchants) and are depicted in the “Konpira Sankei Meisho Zue,” an illustrated guide to Konpira pilgrimages compiled during the [[Bunka era (1804–1818)|Bunka period]]{{R|和}}. Although Kamiyo-ame is known for being sold within the shrine grounds, it is also sold at shops outside the shrine grounds.

== History ==
During the [[Edo period]], visiting [[Kotohira-gū]] (Konpira-san) was as popular as visiting the [[Ise Jingū]]{{R|和}}.

Among the souvenir confections of Kotohira-gū, candy sold in the shrine grounds was especially popular. In the “Tamao-shū” (compiled in [[Enpō 5 (1677)|Enpō 5 (1677)]] by Konishi Kaharu), the candy is referred to as “Konpira no Marudō” (丸糖, round candy){{R|和}}. It is said that at that time, the candy was made using rice offered at Kotohira-gū{{R|和}}.

After World War II, the candy, which had been made from rice, was changed to a sugar-based candy called “Konpira-ame” (round candy). However, as similar products began appearing, around 1950 the shape was changed to a fan shape and renamed “Kamiyo-ame.”{{R|和}}

